---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const post = {
  title: "Getting Started with Astro",
  description: "First steps in building a site with Astro.",
  pubDate: new Date("2026-04-18"),
  tags: ["web-dev", "astro"]
};
---

<BaseLayout lang="en" title={post.title} description={post.description}>
  <article class="blog-post">
    <header class="post-header">
      <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}`} class="back-link">← Back to main</a>
      <h1 class="post-title">{post.title}</h1>
      <div class="post-meta">
        <time datetime={post.pubDate.toISOString()}>
          {post.pubDate.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' })}
        </time>
        <div class="post-tags">
          {post.tags.map(tag => <span class="tag">{tag}</span>)}
        </div>
      </div>
      <img src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/blog/hero-astro.svg`} alt="Astro illustration" class="post-hero" />
    </header>

    <div class="post-content">
      <p>I recently rebuilt my portfolio site using Astro, and it's been a great experience.</p>

      <h2>Why Astro?</h2>

      <p>Astro is a modern static site generator that ships zero JavaScript by default. This makes sites incredibly fast.</p>

      <p>You can still use your favorite framework (React, Vue, Svelte) for interactive components, but only when you need them.</p>

      <h2>Getting started</h2>

      <p>Setting up a new Astro project is simple:</p>

      <pre><code>npm create astro@latest
cd my-project
npm run dev</code></pre>

      <p>That's it. You now have a working Astro site running on localhost:4321.</p>

      <h2>What I like</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fast by default</strong> — No JavaScript unless you explicitly add it</li>
        <li><strong>Simple syntax</strong> — .astro files are just HTML with superpowers</li>
        <li><strong>Great DX</strong> — Hot reload, TypeScript support, and excellent docs</li>
        <li><strong>Framework agnostic</strong> — Use React, Vue, Svelte, or plain HTML</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Perfect for</h2>

      <p>Astro is ideal for content-focused sites: blogs, portfolios, documentation, marketing pages.</p>

      <p>If you're building a highly interactive app, you might want something else. But for static sites? Astro is hard to beat.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
